In a #small pot{}, combine @Basmati Rice{1/2%cup}, @water{3/4%cup}, and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, wash and dry produce.

Core, deseed, and dice @Bell Pepper{1} into 1-inch pieces. Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper and season with @salt{} and @Pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until almost tender, ~{5%minutes}.

> If needed, add splashes of water to help pepper soften.

Add scallion whites and cook until veggies are softened, ~{2%minutes} more. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wash out pan.

Pat @Shrimp{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with @salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add shrimp; cook, stirring occasionally, until shrimp are opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Reduce heat under pan to medium.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145º.

Add @Tomato Paste{1}, @Curry Powder{1%tablespoon}, and @Paprika{1%tsp} to pan with shrimp. Add a pinch of @Chili Flakes{1%tsp} if you like things spicy.

Cook, stirring, until shrimp is fully coated and spices are fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in @Coconut Milk{1}, @water{1/4%cup}, @Sugar{1%tsp}, @Butter{1%tbsp}, and a big pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a simmer, then reduce heat to low. Cook until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes} more.

> Taste and add more sugar if you like a sweeter curry.

Add bell pepper mixture and @Sour Cream{1.5%tbsp}; stir to combine. Taste and season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and season with salt and pepper; divide between #bowls{}.

Top rice with coconut shrimp curry and sprinkle with a pinch of @?Chili Flakes{pinch} if desired. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.